The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Chemplast Sanmar will split the equity shares of the company in a 1:10 ratio. The company?s board of directors has approved the stock split, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. Chemplast shares of Rs 10 each will be split into 10 equity shares of Re 1 each, subject to the shareholders? approval. The board has also approved the proposal to invest Rs 450 crore in setting up a 170,000-tpa greenfield PVC (polyvinyl chloride) project at Cuddalore.

 ING Groep, the Dutch financial-services company, may move some jobs to India to cut costs, the company?s executive board member, Eric Boyer de la Giroday, said. ING and its Indian joint venture ING Vysya Bank may together hire a company to provide back-office services. However, it is not yet finalised what functions the new company will do and how many jobs will be transferred to India.

 SBI Life Insurance has entered into a strategic tie-up with Federal Bank whereby it will provide life insurance cover to borrowers of Federal Bank?s home loans. Called ?Federal Home with Life?, the facility will be offered to Federal Bank home loan borrowers, both existing and new, who will have the option to choose a life insurance cover by paying a one-time premium. The premium can also be paid as part of the housing loan EMIs.

 Blaupunkt has forayed into the truck and coach entertainment segment and is in talks with all coach manufacturers in the country. The company has already supplied 900 basic systems to Karnataka State Road Transport Corporation last year. It expects a Rs 2-4 crore turnover from truck and coach entertainment systems by 2007. 

 Kaya Skin Clinic, Marico Industries? skin care initiative, will invest around Rs 70 crore in two years to expand its clinics and Kaya Skin Zones in India and abroad. The company plans to open approximately 32 clinics and 70 skin zones (consultancy and retail) in the next couple of years. The company is also launching clinics abroad in large formats.

 Hindustan Construction Company will raise $150 million through an issue of foreign currency convertible bonds (fccbs) or global depository receipts or such other financial instruments. The board of directors of the company has approved the issue in one or more tranches, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Howrah Gramin Bank has opened its 60th branch in the district on the occasion of its Silver Jubilee. The regional rural bank has decided to increase its loan disbursal by identifying areas that need financing and by providing better customer-friendly services and infrastructure.

